inline_comments.message:
What is "correct indentation" in Helm?

If the output were not white-space sensitive, I would have done it like this:

{{- define "dcaegen2-services-common._ms-specific-env-vars" -}}
    {{- $global := . }}
    {{- if .Values.applicationEnv }}
        {{- range $envName, $envValue := .Values.applicationEnv }}
            {{- if kindIs "string" $envValue }}
                - name: {{ $envName }}
                  value: {{ $envValue | quote }}
            {{- else }}
                {{- if $envValue.secretUid }}
                    {{- if $envValue.key }}
                        - name: {{ $envName }}
                        {{- include "common.secret.envFromSecretFast" (dict "global" $global "uid" $envValue.secretUid "key" $envValue.key) | nindent 2 }}
                    {{- end }}
               {{- end }}
            {{- end -}}
        {{- end }}
    {{- end }}
{{- end -}}

However, this makes the output indented differently depending on which condition is met.  Seems like templates should generate text that's not indented at all.

Alternatively, we could do this:

{{- define "dcaegen2-services-common._ms-specific-env-vars" -}}
    {{- $global := . }}
    {{- if .Values.applicationEnv }}
        {{- range $envName, $envValue := .Values.applicationEnv }}
            {{- if kindIs "string" $envValue }}
- name: {{ $envName }}
  value: {{ $envValue | quote }}
            {{- else }}
                {{- if $envValue.secretUid }}
                    {{- if $envValue.key }}
- name: {{ $envName }}
  {{- include "common.secret.envFromSecretFast" (dict "global" $global "uid" $envValue.secretUid "key" $envValue.key) | nindent 2 }}
                    {{- end }}
               {{- end }}
            {{- end -}}
        {{- end }}
    {{- end }}
{{- end -}}

To me, that's no more readable.  In fact, I find it harder to see what's going on.  Using 2-space indentation rather than 4 makes it even worse, in my view.

Please make a clear statement about how you expect Helm to be indented.  I've got more changes coming, and other people on the DCAE team are also making changes, so we need to know--not just indentation rules, but any other standards you expect to be met.  It takes days or weeks to cycle through even a small change to OOM, so it's best if we get it "right" at the beginning, rather than going through several cycles to make everything "correct".

Perhaps this?

{{- define "dcaegen2-services-common._ms-specific-env-vars" -}}
  {{- $global := . }}
  {{- if .Values.applicationEnv }}
    {{- range $envName, $envValue := .Values.applicationEnv }}
      {{- if kindIs "string" $envValue }}
        {{- printf "- name: %s\n  value: %s\n" $envName ($envValue | quote) }}
      {{- else }}
        {{- if $envValue.secretUid }}
          {{- if $envValue.key }}
            {{- $secret := include "common.secret.envFromSecretFast" (dict "global" $global "uid" $envValue.secretUid "key" $envValue.key) | indent 2 -}}
            {{- printf "- name: %s\n%s\n" $envName $secret }}
          {{- end }}
        {{- end }}
      {{- end -}}
    {{- end }}
  {{- end }}
{{- end -}}

I prefer 4-space indentation (because 2-space indentation overlaps with the 3-character opening sequence "{{-"), but the convention appears to be 2 spaces.

Sorry for not being precise enough.

So usually we are using style where we indent only the "technical lines" (those that are starting with {{ and just leave "rest of the text" not indented at all (checkout common/common for examples).
Sylvain tends to sometimes use a different style where he indents stuff inside {{ like:
 {{ if a }}
 {{   if b }}
 DoSomeStupidStuff
 {{   end }}
 {{ end }}

so we haven't yet found a consisting indent style so whatever you decide to do is fine as long as it's clear and readable:)
